# **Technocapitalism** refers to a contemporary economic and social system characterized by the dominance of technology-driven capital, where [technological innovation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technological_innovation) becomes a central component of [economic growth](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_growth) and [wealth accumulation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_accumulation). This term encapsulates the interplay between [technology](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology) and [capitalism](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalism), highlighting how advancements in technology influence economic structures, [labor markets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_markets), and [social relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_relations). A significant aspect of technocapitalism is the rise of the intangible economy, which is marked by the increasing importance of non-physical assets such as [intellectual property](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intellectual_property), [brand value](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brand_valuation), and digital services. This shift has led to new forms of economic centralization, where a few [tech giants](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tech_Giants) dominate markets due to their ability to scale rapidly and leverage synergies across different sectors.
